Section 1: Q&A; Pairs

Example 1.1

User

What is deep learning?
AI Response

Deep learning is a subset of machine learning that uses multi-layered neural networks to learn
representations of data. It excels at tasks like image recognition, NLP, and speech synthesis.

Example 1.2

User

What is a convolutional neural network?
AI Response

A CNN uses convolutional layers to automatically learn spatial features from images. Pooling layers reduce
dimensionality. CNNs are the standard for image classification and detection tasks.

Example 1.3

User

What is gradient descent?
AI Response

Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm that iteratively adjusts model parameters in the direction
opposite to the gradient of the loss function to find a minimum.

Example 1.4

User

What is cross-validation?
AI Response

Cross-validation splits data into k folds, training on k-1 and validating on one, rotating until all folds serve as
validation. Results are averaged for robust performance estimation.

Example 1.5

User

What is regularization?
AI Response

Regularization adds a penalty to the loss function to discourage model complexity. L1 promotes sparsity; L2
penalizes large weights. Both reduce overfitting.

Example 1.6

User

What is overfitting?
AI Response

Overfitting occurs when a model learns training data too well—including noise—causing poor generalization
to new data. Symptoms include high train accuracy but low validation accuracy.

Example 1.7

User

What is a neural network?
AI Response



A neural network is a series of algorithms modeled after the human brain, consisting of input, hidden, and
output layers, with weights adjusted during training to minimize prediction error.

Example 1.8

User

What is K-means clustering?
AI Response

K-means partitions data into K clusters by iteratively assigning points to the nearest centroid and updating
centroids as the mean of assigned points, minimizing intra-cluster variance.

Example 1.9

User

What is attention mechanism?
AI Response

Attention allows a model to focus on relevant input parts during output generation. Self-attention in
transformers computes weighted relationships between all token pairs.

Example 1.10

User

What is a loss function?
AI Response

A loss function quantifies the difference between a model's predictions and the actual targets. Examples
include Mean Squared Error for regression and Cross-Entropy Loss for classification.



